  version: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 51ee3e37f5ded7941ab6216610f6fc67, type: 2}
  description: 
  chapters:
  - verses:
    - title: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Charge to Joshua"
      content: "  After the death of Moses the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        servant, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> spoke to Joshua son of Nun, Moses\u2019
        assistant. He said, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CMoses my servant is dead. Therefore, the time has come for
        you to lead these people, the Israelites, across the Jordan River into the
        land I am giving them. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I promise you what I promised Moses: \u2018Wherever you set foot,
        you will be on land I have given you\u2014 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "from the Negev wilderness in the south to the Lebanon mountains in
        the north, from the Euphrates River in the east to the Mediterranean Sea[[COMMENT(0)]]
        in the west, including all the land of the Hittites.\u2019 "
      comments:
      - number: '1:4 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Great Sea.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'No one will be able to stand against you as long as you live. For
        I will be with you as I was with Moses. I will not fail you or abandon you.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBe strong and courageous, for you are the one who will lead
        these people to possess all the land I swore to their ancestors I would give
        them. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Be strong and very courageous. Be careful to obey all the instructions
        Moses gave you. Do not deviate from them, turning either to the right or
        to the left. Then you will be successful in everything you do. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Study this Book of Instruction continually. Meditate on it day and
        night so you will be sure to obey everything written in it. Only then will
        you prosper and succeed in all you do. '
      comments: []
    - title: "Joshua\u2019s Charge to the Israelites"
      content: "This is my command\u2014be strong and courageous! Do not be afraid
        or discouraged. For the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God is with you
        wherever you go.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Joshua then commanded the officers of Israel, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CGo through the camp and tell the people to get their provisions
        ready. In three days you will cross the Jordan River and take possession
        of the land the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God is giving you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Joshua called together the tribes of Reuben, Gad, and the half-tribe
        of Manasseh. He told them, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CRemember what Moses, the servant of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        commanded you: \u2018The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God is giving you
        a place of rest. He has given you this land.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Your wives, children, and livestock may remain here in the land Moses
        assigned to you on the east side of the Jordan River. But your strong warriors,
        fully armed, must lead the other tribes across the Jordan to help them conquer
        their territory. Stay with them '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "until the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> gives them rest, as he has
        given you rest, and until they, too, possess the land the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        your God is giving them. Only then may you return and settle here on the
        east side of the Jordan River in the land that Moses, the servant of the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, assigned to you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They answered Joshua, \u201CWe will do whatever you command us, and
        we will go wherever you send us. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'We will obey you just as we obeyed Moses. And may the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        your God be with you as he was with Moses. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Rahab Protects the Spies
      content: "  Then Joshua secretly sent out two spies from the Israelite camp
        at Acacia Grove.[[COMMENT(0)]] He instructed them, \u201CScout out the land
        on the other side of the Jordan River, especially around Jericho.\u201D So
        the two men set out and came to the house of a prostitute named Rahab and
        stayed there that night.  "
      comments:
      - number: '2:1 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Shittim.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "But someone told the king of Jericho, \u201CSome Israelites have
        come here tonight to spy out the land.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So the king of Jericho sent orders to Rahab: \u201CBring out the
        men who have come into your house, for they have come here to spy out the
        whole land.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Rahab had hidden the two men, but she replied, \u201CYes, the men
        were here earlier, but I didn\u2019t know where they were from. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They left the town at dusk, as the gates were about to close. I don\u2019t
        know where they went. If you hurry, you can probably catch up with them.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: '(Actually, she had taken them up to the roof and hidden them beneath
        bundles of flax she had laid out.) '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So the king\u2019s men went looking for the spies along the road
        leading to the shallow crossings of the Jordan River. And as soon as the
        king\u2019s men had left, the gate of Jericho was shut.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Before the spies went to sleep that night, Rahab went up on the roof
        to talk with them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CI know the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has given you this land,\u201D
        she told them. \u201CWe are all afraid of you. Everyone in the land is living
        in terror. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: For we have heard how the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> made a dry path
        for you through the Red Sea[[COMMENT(0)]] when you left Egypt. And we know
        what you did to Sihon and Og, the two Amorite kings east of the Jordan River,
        whose people you completely destroyed.[[COMMENT(1)]]<smallcaps>  </smallcaps>
      comments:
      - number: '2:10a '
        content: Hebrew <b>sea of reeds.</b>
      - number: '2:10b '
        content: The Hebrew term used here refers to the complete consecration of
          things or people to the <span class="ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf">Lord</span>,
          either by destroying them or by giving them as an offering.
    - title: 
      content: 'No wonder our hearts have melted in fear! No one has the courage
        to fight after hearing such things. For the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your
        God is the supreme God of the heavens above and the earth below.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNow swear to me by the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> that you
        will be kind to me and my family since I have helped you. Give me some guarantee
        that "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "when Jericho is conquered, you will let me live, along with my father
        and mother, my brothers and sisters, and all their families.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWe offer our own lives as a guarantee for your safety,\u201D
        the men agreed. \u201CIf you don\u2019t betray us, we will keep our promise
        and be kind to you when the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> gives us the land.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then, since Rahab\u2019s house was built into the town wall, she
        let them down by a rope through the window. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CEscape to the hill country,\u201D she told them. \u201CHide
        there for three days from the men searching for you. Then, when they have
        returned, you can go on your way.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Before they left, the men told her, \u201CWe will be bound by the
        oath we have taken only if you follow these instructions. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When we come into the land, you must leave this scarlet rope hanging
        from the window through which you let us down. And all your family members\u2014your
        father, mother, brothers, and all your relatives\u2014must be here inside
        the house. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'If they go out into the street and are killed, it will not be our
        fault. But if anyone lays a hand on people inside this house, we will accept
        the responsibility for their death. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "If you betray us, however, we are not bound by this oath in any way.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CI accept your terms,\u201D she replied. And she sent them on
        their way, leaving the scarlet rope hanging from the window.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The spies went up into the hill country and stayed there three days.
        The men who were chasing them searched everywhere along the road, but they
        finally returned without success.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the two spies came down from the hill country, crossed the Jordan
        River, and reported to Joshua all that had happened to them. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Israelites Cross the Jordan
      content: '  Early the next morning Joshua and all the Israelites left Acacia
        Grove[[COMMENT(0)]] and arrived at the banks of the Jordan River, where they
        camped before crossing. '
      comments:
      - number: '3:1 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Shittim.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Three days later the Israelite officers went through the camp, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "giving these instructions to the people: \u201CWhen you see the Levitical
        priests carrying the Ark of the Covenant of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        your God, move out from your positions and follow them. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Since you have never traveled this way before, they will guide you.
        Stay about half a mile[[COMMENT(0)]] behind them, keeping a clear distance
        between you and the Ark. Make sure you don\u2019t come any closer.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '3:4 '
        content: Hebrew <b>about 2,000 cubits </b>[920 meters].
    - title: 
      content: "Then Joshua told the people, \u201CPurify yourselves, for tomorrow
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will do great wonders among you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "In the morning Joshua said to the priests, \u201CLift up the Ark
        of the Covenant and lead the people across the river.\u201D And so they started
        out and went ahead of the people.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> told Joshua, \u201CToday I will begin
        to make you a great leader in the eyes of all the Israelites. They will know
        that I am with you, just as I was with Moses. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Give this command to the priests who carry the Ark of the Covenant:
        \u2018When you reach the banks of the Jordan River, take a few steps into
        the river and stop there.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Joshua told the Israelites, \u201CCome and listen to what the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God says. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Today you will know that the living God is among you. He will surely
        drive out the Canaanites, Hittites, Hivites, Perizzites, Girgashites, Amorites,
        and Jebusites ahead of you. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Look, the Ark of the Covenant, which belongs to the Lord of the whole
        earth, will lead you across the Jordan River! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Now choose twelve men from the tribes of Israel, one from each tribe. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The priests will carry the Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the Lord of all the earth. As soon as their feet touch the water, the flow
        of water will be cut off upstream, and the river will stand up like a wall.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the people left their camp to cross the Jordan, and the priests
        who were carrying the Ark of the Covenant went ahead of them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "It was the harvest season, and the Jordan was overflowing its banks.
        But as soon as the feet of the priests who were carrying the Ark touched
        the water at the river\u2019s edge, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'the water above that point began backing up a great distance away
        at a town called Adam, which is near Zarethan. And the water below that point
        flowed on to the Dead Sea[[COMMENT(0)]] until the riverbed was dry. Then
        all the people crossed over near the town of Jericho.  '
      comments:
      - number: '3:16 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the sea of the Arabah, the Salt Sea.</b>
  - verses:
    - title: Memorials to the Jordan Crossing
      content: '  When all the people had crossed the Jordan, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        said to Joshua, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNow choose twelve men, one from each tribe. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Tell them, \u2018Take twelve stones from the very place where the
        priests are standing in the middle of the Jordan. Carry them out and pile
        them up at the place where you will camp tonight.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Joshua called together the twelve men he had chosen\u2014one from
        each of the tribes of Israel. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He told them, \u201CGo into the middle of the Jordan, in front of
        the Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God. Each of you must pick
        up one stone and carry it out on your shoulder\u2014twelve stones in all,
        one for each of the twelve tribes of Israel. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "We will use these stones to build a memorial. In the future your
        children will ask you, \u2018What do these stones mean?\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then you can tell them, \u2018They remind us that the Jordan River
        stopped flowing when the Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Covenant
        went across.\u2019 These stones will stand as a memorial among the people
        of Israel forever.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the men did as Joshua had commanded them. They took twelve stones
        from the middle of the Jordan River, one for each tribe, just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had told Joshua. They carried them to the place where they camped for the
        night and constructed the memorial there.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Joshua also set up another pile of twelve stones in the middle of
        the Jordan, at the place where the priests who carried the Ark of the Covenant
        were standing. And they are there to this day.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The priests who were carrying the Ark stood in the middle of the
        river until all of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s commands that Moses
        had given to Joshua were carried out. Meanwhile, the people hurried across
        the riverbed. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And when everyone was safely on the other side, the priests crossed
        over with the Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> as the people watched.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The armed warriors from the tribes of Reuben, Gad, and the half-tribe
        of Manasseh led the Israelites across the Jordan, just as Moses had directed. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "These armed men\u2014about 40,000 strong\u2014were ready for battle,
        and the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> was with them as they crossed over to
        the plains of Jericho.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'That day the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> made Joshua a great leader
        in the eyes of all the Israelites, and for the rest of his life they revered
        him as much as they had revered Moses.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had said to Joshua, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CCommand the priests carrying the Ark of the Covenant[[COMMENT(0)]]
        to come up out of the riverbed.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '4:16 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Ark of the Testimony.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'So Joshua gave the command. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "As soon as the priests carrying the Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Covenant came up out of the riverbed and their feet were on high ground,
        the water of the Jordan returned and overflowed its banks as before.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The people crossed the Jordan on the tenth day of the first month.[[COMMENT(0)]]
        Then they camped at Gilgal, just east of Jericho. '
      comments:
      - number: '4:19 '
        content: This day in the ancient Hebrew lunar calendar occurred in late March,
          April, or early May.
    - title: 
      content: 'It was there at Gilgal that Joshua piled up the twelve stones taken
        from the Jordan River.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Joshua said to the Israelites, \u201CIn the future your children
        will ask, \u2018What do these stones mean?\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then you can tell them, \u2018This is where the Israelites crossed
        the Jordan on dry ground.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God dried up the river right
        before your eyes, and he kept it dry until you were all across, just as he
        did at the Red Sea[[COMMENT(0)]] when he dried it up until we had all crossed
        over. '
      comments:
      - number: '4:23 '
        content: Hebrew <b>sea of reeds.</b>
  - verses:
    - title: Israel Reestablishes Covenant Ceremonies
      content: '  When all the Amorite kings west of the Jordan and all the Canaanite
        kings who lived along the Mediterranean coast[[COMMENT(0)]] heard how the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had dried up the Jordan River so the people of
        Israel could cross, they lost heart and were paralyzed with fear because
        of them.  '
      comments:
      - number: '5:1 '
        content: Hebrew <b>along the sea.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "At that time the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> told Joshua, \u201CMake
        flint knives and circumcise this second generation of Israelites.[[COMMENT(0)]]\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '5:2 '
        content: Or <b>circumcise the Israelites a second time.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'So Joshua made flint knives and circumcised the entire male population
        of Israel at Gibeath-haaraloth.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '5:3 '
        content: "<b>Gibeath-haaraloth </b>means \u201Chill of foreskins.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: 'Joshua had to circumcise them because all the men who were old enough
        to fight in battle when they left Egypt had died in the wilderness. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Those who left Egypt had all been circumcised, but none of those
        born after the Exodus, during the years in the wilderness, had been circumcised. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The Israelites had traveled in the wilderness for forty years until
        all the men who were old enough to fight in battle when they left Egypt had
        died. For they had disobeyed the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, and the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        vowed he would not let them enter the land he had sworn to give us\u2014a
        land flowing with milk and honey. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Joshua circumcised their sons\u2014those who had grown up to take
        their fathers\u2019 places\u2014for they had not been circumcised on the
        way to the Promised Land. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After all the males had been circumcised, they rested in the camp
        until they were healed.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Joshua, \u201CToday
        I have rolled away the shame of your slavery in Egypt.\u201D So that place
        has been called Gilgal[[COMMENT(0)]] to this day.  "
      comments:
      - number: '5:9 '
        content: "<b>Gilgal </b>sounds like the Hebrew word <b>galal, </b>meaning
          \u201Cto roll.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: 'While the Israelites were camped at Gilgal on the plains of Jericho,
        they celebrated Passover on the evening of the fourteenth day of the first
        month.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '5:10 '
        content: This day in the ancient Hebrew lunar calendar occurred in late March,
          April, or early May.
    - title: 
      content: 'The very next day they began to eat unleavened bread and roasted
        grain harvested from the land. '
      comments: []
    - title: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Commander Confronts Joshua"
      content: 'No manna appeared on the day they first ate from the crops of the
        land, and it was never seen again. So from that time on the Israelites ate
        from the crops of Canaan.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When Joshua was near the town of Jericho, he looked up and saw a
        man standing in front of him with sword in hand. Joshua went up to him and
        demanded, \u201CAre you friend or foe?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNeither one,\u201D he replied. \u201CI am the commander of
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s army.\u201DAt this, Joshua fell with
        his face to the ground in reverence. \u201CI am at your command,\u201D Joshua
        said. \u201CWhat do you want your servant to do?\u201D  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Fall of Jericho
      content: '  Now the gates of Jericho were tightly shut because the people were
        afraid of the Israelites. No one was allowed to go out or in. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Joshua, \u201CI have
        given you Jericho, its king, and all its strong warriors. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You and your fighting men should march around the town once a day
        for six days. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Seven priests will walk ahead of the Ark, each carrying a ram\u2019s
        horn. On the seventh day you are to march around the town seven times, with
        the priests blowing the horns. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When you hear the priests give one long blast on the rams\u2019 horns,
        have all the people shout as loud as they can. Then the walls of the town
        will collapse, and the people can charge straight into the town.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Joshua called together the priests and said, \u201CTake up the
        Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Covenant, and assign seven
        priests to walk in front of it, each carrying a ram\u2019s horn.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he gave orders to the people: \u201CMarch around the town, and
        the armed men will lead the way in front of the Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "After Joshua spoke to the people, the seven priests with the rams\u2019
        horns started marching in the presence of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        blowing the horns as they marched. And the Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Covenant followed behind them. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Some of the armed men marched in front of the priests with the horns
        and some behind the Ark, with the priests continually blowing the horns. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CDo not shout; do not even talk,\u201D Joshua commanded. \u201CNot
        a single word from any of you until I tell you to shout. Then shout!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> was carried around
        the town once that day, and then everyone returned to spend the night in
        the camp.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Joshua got up early the next morning, and the priests again carried
        the Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The seven priests with the rams\u2019 horns marched in front of the
        Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, blowing their horns. Again the armed
        men marched both in front of the priests with the horns and behind the Ark
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. All this time the priests were blowing
        their horns. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'On the second day they again marched around the town once and returned
        to the camp. They followed this pattern for six days.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'On the seventh day the Israelites got up at dawn and marched around
        the town as they had done before. But this time they went around the town
        seven times. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The seventh time around, as the priests sounded the long blast on
        their horns, Joshua commanded the people, \u201CShout! For the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has given you the town! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Jericho and everything in it must be completely destroyed[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>
        as an offering to the </smallcaps><smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. Only Rahab
        the prostitute and the others in her house will be spared, for she protected
        our spies.  '
      comments:
      - number: '6:17 '
        content: The Hebrew term used here refers to the complete consecration of
          things or people to the <span class="ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf">Lord</span>,
          either by destroying them or by giving them as an offering; similarly in
          6:18, 21.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CDo not take any of the things set apart for destruction, or
        you yourselves will be completely destroyed, and you will bring trouble on
        the camp of Israel. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Everything made from silver, gold, bronze, or iron is sacred to the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and must be brought into his treasury.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When the people heard the sound of the rams\u2019 horns, they shouted
        as loud as they could. Suddenly, the walls of Jericho collapsed, and the
        Israelites charged straight into the town and captured it. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They completely destroyed everything in it with their swords\u2014men
        and women, young and old, cattle, sheep, goats, and donkeys.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Meanwhile, Joshua said to the two spies, \u201CKeep your promise.
        Go to the prostitute\u2019s house and bring her out, along with all her family.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The men who had been spies went in and brought out Rahab, her father,
        mother, brothers, and all the other relatives who were with her. They moved
        her whole family to a safe place near the camp of Israel.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the Israelites burned the town and everything in it. Only the
        things made from silver, gold, bronze, or iron were kept for the treasury
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s house. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Joshua spared Rahab the prostitute and her relatives who were
        with her in the house, because she had hidden the spies Joshua sent to Jericho.
        And she lives among the Israelites to this day.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "At that time Joshua invoked this curse:\u201CMay the curse of the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> fall on anyonewho tries to rebuild the town of
        Jericho.At the cost of his firstborn son,he will lay its foundation.At the
        cost of his youngest son,he will set up its gates.\u201D  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Ai Defeats the Israelites
      content: '  But Israel violated the instructions about the things set apart
        for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> A man named
        Achan had stolen some of these dedicated things, so the </smallcaps><smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        was very angry with the Israelites. Achan was the son of Carmi, a descendant
        of Zimri[[COMMENT(1)]] son of Zerah, of the tribe of Judah.  '
      comments:
      - number: '7:1a '
        content: The Hebrew term used here refers to the complete consecration of
          things or people to the <span class="ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf">Lord</span>,
          either by destroying them or by giving them as an offering; similarly in
          7:11, 12, 13, 15.
      - number: '7:1b '
        content: As in parallel text at 1 Chr 2:6; Hebrew reads <b>Zabdi. </b>Also
          in 7:17, 18.
    - title: 
      content: 'Joshua sent some of his men from Jericho to spy out the town of Ai,
        east of Bethel, near Beth-aven. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When they returned, they told Joshua, \u201CThere\u2019s no need
        for all of us to go up there; it won\u2019t take more than two or three thousand
        men to attack Ai. Since there are so few of them, don\u2019t make all our
        people struggle to go up there.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So approximately 3,000 warriors were sent, but they were soundly
        defeated. The men of Ai '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'chased the Israelites from the town gate as far as the quarries,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        and they killed about thirty-six who were retreating down the slope. The
        Israelites were paralyzed with fear at this turn of events, and their courage
        melted away.  '
      comments:
      - number: '7:5 '
        content: Or <b>as far as Shebarim.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Joshua and the elders of Israel tore their clothing in dismay, threw
        dust on their heads, and bowed face down to the ground before the Ark of
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> until evening. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Joshua cried out, \u201COh, Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        why did you bring us across the Jordan River if you are going to let the
        Amorites kill us? If only we had been content to stay on the other side! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Lord, what can I say now that Israel has fled from its enemies? '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For when the Canaanites and all the other people living in the land
        hear about it, they will surround us and wipe our name off the face of the
        earth. And then what will happen to the honor of your great name?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Joshua, \u201CGet up!
        Why are you lying on your face like this? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Israel has sinned and broken my covenant! They have stolen some of
        the things that I commanded must be set apart for me. And they have not only
        stolen them but have lied about it and hidden the things among their own
        belongings. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'That is why the Israelites are running from their enemies in defeat.
        For now Israel itself has been set apart for destruction. I will not remain
        with you any longer unless you destroy the things among you that were set
        apart for destruction.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CGet up! Command the people to purify themselves in preparation
        for tomorrow. For this is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of
        Israel, says: Hidden among you, O Israel, are things set apart for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.
        You will never defeat your enemies until you remove these things from among
        you.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIn the morning you must present yourselves by tribes, and the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will point out the tribe to which the guilty
        man belongs. That tribe must come forward with its clans, and the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        will point out the guilty clan. That clan will then come forward, and the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will point out the guilty family. Finally, each
        member of the guilty family must come forward one by one. "
      comments: []
    - title: "Achan\u2019s Sin"
      content: "The one who has stolen what was set apart for destruction will himself
        be burned with fire, along with everything he has, for he has broken the
        covenant of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and has done a horrible thing
        in Israel.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Early the next morning Joshua brought the tribes of Israel before
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, and the tribe of Judah was singled out. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the clans of Judah came forward, and the clan of Zerah was singled
        out. Then the families of Zerah came forward, and the family of Zimri was
        singled out. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Every member of Zimri\u2019s family was brought forward person by
        person, and Achan was singled out.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Joshua said to Achan, \u201CMy son, give glory to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of Israel, by telling the truth. Make your confession and tell me
        what you have done. Don\u2019t hide it from me.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Achan replied, \u201CIt is true! I have sinned against the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of Israel. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Among the plunder I saw a beautiful robe from Babylon,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        200 silver coins,[[COMMENT(1)]] and a bar of gold weighing more than a pound.[[COMMENT(2)]]
        I wanted them so much that I took them. They are hidden in the ground beneath
        my tent, with the silver buried deeper than the rest.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '7:21a '
        content: Hebrew <b>Shinar.</b>
      - number: '7:21b '
        content: Hebrew <b>200 shekels of silver, </b>about 5 pounds or 2.3 kilograms
          in weight.
      - number: '7:21c '
        content: Hebrew <b>50 shekels, </b>about 20 ounces or 570 grams in weight.
    - title: 
      content: 'So Joshua sent some men to make a search. They ran to the tent and
        found the stolen goods hidden there, just as Achan had said, with the silver
        buried beneath the rest. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They took the things from the tent and brought them to Joshua and
        all the Israelites. Then they laid them on the ground in the presence of
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Joshua and all the Israelites took Achan, the silver, the robe,
        the bar of gold, his sons, daughters, cattle, donkeys, sheep, goats, tent,
        and everything he had, and they brought them to the valley of Achor. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Joshua said to Achan, \u201CWhy have you brought trouble on
        us? The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will now bring trouble on you.\u201D
        And all the Israelites stoned Achan and his family and burned their bodies. "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Israelites Defeat Ai
      content: "  Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Joshua, \u201CDo not
        be afraid or discouraged. Take all your fighting men and attack Ai, for I
        have given you the king of Ai, his people, his town, and his land. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You will destroy them as you destroyed Jericho and its king. But
        this time you may keep the plunder and the livestock for yourselves. Set
        an ambush behind the town.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Joshua and all the fighting men set out to attack Ai. Joshua chose
        30,000 of his best warriors and sent them out at night '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "with these orders: \u201CHide in ambush close behind the town and
        be ready for action. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When our main army attacks, the men of Ai will come out to fight
        as they did before, and we will run away from them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "We will let them chase us until we have drawn them away from the
        town. For they will say, \u2018The Israelites are running away from us as
        they did before.\u2019 Then, while we are running from them, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'you will jump up from your ambush and take possession of the town,
        for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God will give it to you. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Set the town on fire, as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has commanded.
        You have your orders.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So they left and went to the place of ambush between Bethel and the
        west side of Ai. But Joshua remained among the people in the camp that night. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Early the next morning Joshua roused his men and started toward Ai,
        accompanied by the elders of Israel. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'All the fighting men who were with Joshua marched in front of the
        town and camped on the north side of Ai, with a valley between them and the
        town. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'That night Joshua sent about 5,000 men to lie in ambush between Bethel
        and Ai, on the west side of the town. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So they stationed the main army north of the town and the ambush
        west of the town. Joshua himself spent that night in the valley.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When the king of Ai saw the Israelites across the valley, he and
        all his army hurried out early in the morning and attacked the Israelites
        at a place overlooking the Jordan Valley.[[COMMENT(0)]] But he didn\u2019t
        realize there was an ambush behind the town. "
      comments:
      - number: '8:14 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Arabah.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Joshua and the Israelite army fled toward the wilderness as though
        they were badly beaten. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then all the men in the town were called out to chase after them.
        In this way, they were lured away from the town. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'There was not a man left in Ai or Bethel[[COMMENT(0)]] who did not
        chase after the Israelites, and the town was left wide open.  '
      comments:
      - number: '8:17 '
        content: Some manuscripts lack <b>or Bethel.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Joshua, \u201CPoint
        the spear in your hand toward Ai, for I will hand the town over to you.\u201D
        Joshua did as he was commanded. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As soon as Joshua gave this signal, all the men in ambush jumped
        up from their position and poured into the town. They quickly captured it
        and set it on fire.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When the men of Ai looked behind them, smoke from the town was filling
        the sky, and they had nowhere to go. For the Israelites who had fled in the
        direction of the wilderness now turned on their pursuers. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Joshua and all the other Israelites saw that the ambush had
        succeeded and that smoke was rising from the town, they turned and attacked
        the men of Ai. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Meanwhile, the Israelites who were inside the town came out and attacked
        the enemy from the rear. So the men of Ai were caught in the middle, with
        Israelite fighters on both sides. Israel attacked them, and not a single
        person survived or escaped. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Only the king of Ai was taken alive and brought to Joshua.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When the Israelite army finished chasing and killing all the men
        of Ai in the open fields, they went back and finished off everyone inside. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So the entire population of Ai, including men and women, was wiped
        out that day\u201412,000 in all. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: For Joshua kept holding out his spear until everyone who had lived
        in Ai was completely destroyed.[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>  </smallcaps>
      comments:
      - number: '8:26 '
        content: The Hebrew term used here refers to the complete consecration of
          things or people to the <span class="ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf">Lord</span>,
          either by destroying them or by giving them as an offering.
    - title: 
      content: 'Only the livestock and the treasures of the town were not destroyed,
        for the Israelites kept these as plunder for themselves, as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had commanded Joshua. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Joshua burned the town of Ai,[[COMMENT(0)]] and it became a permanent
        mound of ruins, desolate to this very day.  '
      comments:
      - number: '8:28 '
        content: "<b>Ai </b>means \u201Cruin.\u201D"
    - title: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Covenant Renewed"
      content: 'Joshua impaled the king of Ai on a sharpened pole and left him there
        until evening. At sunset the Israelites took down the body, as Joshua commanded,
        and threw it in front of the town gate. They piled a great heap of stones
        over him that can still be seen today.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Joshua built an altar to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the
        God of Israel, on Mount Ebal. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He followed the commands that Moses the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        servant had written in the Book of Instruction: \u201CMake me an altar from
        stones that are uncut and have not been shaped with iron tools.\u201D[[COMMENT(0)]]
        Then on the altar they presented burnt offerings and peace offerings to the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. "
      comments:
      - number: '8:31 '
        content: Exod 20:25; Deut 27:5-6.
    - title: 
      content: 'And as the Israelites watched, Joshua copied onto the stones of the
        altar[[COMMENT(0)]] the instructions Moses had given them.  '
      comments:
      - number: '8:32 '
        content: Hebrew <b>onto the stones.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "Then all the Israelites\u2014foreigners and native-born alike\u2014along
        with the elders, officers, and judges, were divided into two groups. One
        group stood in front of Mount Gerizim, the other in front of Mount Ebal.
        Each group faced the other, and between them stood the Levitical priests
        carrying the Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Covenant. This
        was all done according to the commands that Moses, the servant of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        had previously given for blessing the people of Israel.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Joshua then read to them all the blessings and curses Moses had written
        in the Book of Instruction. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Gibeonites Deceive Israel
      content: '  Now all the kings west of the Jordan River heard about what had
        happened. These were the kings of the Hittites, Amorites, Canaanites, Perizzites,
        Hivites, and Jebusites, who lived in the hill country, in the western foothills,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        and along the coast of the Mediterranean Sea[[COMMENT(1)]] as far north as
        the Lebanon mountains. '
      comments:
      - number: '9:1a '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Shephelah.</b>
      - number: '9:1b '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Great Sea.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'These kings combined their armies to fight as one against Joshua
        and the Israelites.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But when the people of Gibeon heard what Joshua had done to Jericho
        and Ai, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'they resorted to deception to save themselves. They sent ambassadors
        to Joshua, loading their donkeys with weathered saddlebags and old, patched
        wineskins. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They put on worn-out, patched sandals and ragged clothes. And the
        bread they took with them was dry and moldy. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When they arrived at the camp of Israel at Gilgal, they told Joshua
        and the men of Israel, \u201CWe have come from a distant land to ask you
        to make a peace treaty with us.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The Israelites replied to these Hivites, \u201CHow do we know you
        don\u2019t live nearby? For if you do, we cannot make a treaty with you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They replied, \u201CWe are your servants.\u201D\u201CBut who are
        you?\u201D Joshua demanded. \u201CWhere do you come from?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They answered, \u201CYour servants have come from a very distant
        country. We have heard of the might of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your
        God and of all he did in Egypt. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "We have also heard what he did to the two Amorite kings east of the
        Jordan River\u2014King Sihon of Heshbon and King Og of Bashan (who lived
        in Ashtaroth). "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So our elders and all our people instructed us, \u2018Take supplies
        for a long journey. Go meet with the people of Israel and tell them, \u201CWe
        are your servants; please make a treaty with us.\u201D\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis bread was hot from the ovens when we left our homes. But
        now, as you can see, it is dry and moldy. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "These wineskins were new when we filled them, but now they are old
        and split open. And our clothing and sandals are worn out from our very long
        journey.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the Israelites examined their food, but they did not consult the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Joshua made a peace treaty with them and guaranteed their safety,
        and the leaders of the community ratified their agreement with a binding
        oath.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Three days after making the treaty, they learned that these people
        actually lived nearby! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The Israelites set out at once to investigate and reached their towns
        in three days. The names of these towns were Gibeon, Kephirah, Beeroth, and
        Kiriath-jearim. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But the Israelites did not attack the towns, for the Israelite leaders
        had made a vow to them in the name of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the
        God of Israel.The people of Israel grumbled against their leaders because
        of the treaty. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the leaders replied, \u201CSince we have sworn an oath in the
        presence of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of Israel, we cannot
        touch them. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'This is what we must do. We must let them live, for divine anger
        would come upon us if we broke our oath. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Let them live.\u201D So they made them woodcutters and water carriers
        for the entire community, as the Israelite leaders directed.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Joshua called together the Gibeonites and said, \u201CWhy did you
        lie to us? Why did you say that you live in a distant land when you live
        right here among us? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "May you be cursed! From now on you will always be servants who cut
        wood and carry water for the house of my God.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They replied, \u201CWe did it because we\u2014your servants\u2014were
        clearly told that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God commanded his
        servant Moses to give you this entire land and to destroy all the people
        living in it. So we feared greatly for our lives because of you. That is
        why we have done this. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Now we are at your mercy\u2014do to us whatever you think is right.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Joshua did not allow the people of Israel to kill them. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Israel Defeats the Southern Armies
      content: '  Adoni-zedek, king of Jerusalem, heard that Joshua had captured
        and completely destroyed[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> Ai and killed its king,
        just as he had destroyed the town of Jericho and killed its king. He also
        learned that the Gibeonites had made peace with Israel and were now their
        allies. </smallcaps>'
      comments:
      - number: '10:1 '
        content: The Hebrew term used here refers to the complete consecration of
          things or people to the <span class="ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf">Lord</span>,
          either by destroying them or by giving them as an offering; also in 10:28,
          35, 37, 39, 40.
    - title: 
      content: "He and his people became very afraid when they heard all this because
        Gibeon was a large town\u2014as large as the royal cities and larger than
        Ai. And the Gibeonite men were strong warriors.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So King Adoni-zedek of Jerusalem sent messengers to several other
        kings: Hoham of Hebron, Piram of Jarmuth, Japhia of Lachish, and Debir of
        Eglon. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CCome and help me destroy Gibeon,\u201D he urged them, \u201Cfor
        they have made peace with Joshua and the people of Israel.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So these five Amorite kings combined their armies for a united attack.
        They moved all their troops into place and attacked Gibeon.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The men of Gibeon quickly sent messengers to Joshua at his camp in
        Gilgal. \u201CDon\u2019t abandon your servants now!\u201D they pleaded. \u201CCome
        at once! Save us! Help us! For all the Amorite kings who live in the hill
        country have joined forces to attack us.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Joshua and his entire army, including his best warriors, left
        Gilgal and set out for Gibeon. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CDo not be afraid of them,\u201D the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        said to Joshua, \u201Cfor I have given you victory over them. Not a single
        one of them will be able to stand up to you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Joshua traveled all night from Gilgal and took the Amorite armies
        by surprise. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> threw them into a panic, and the
        Israelites slaughtered great numbers of them at Gibeon. Then the Israelites
        chased the enemy along the road to Beth-horon, killing them all along the
        way to Azekah and Makkedah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As the Amorites retreated down the road from Beth-horon, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        destroyed them with a terrible hailstorm from heaven that continued until
        they reached Azekah. The hail killed more of the enemy than the Israelites
        killed with the sword.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "On the day the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> gave the Israelites victory
        over the Amorites, Joshua prayed to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> in front
        of all the people of Israel. He said,\u201CLet the sun stand still over Gibeon,and
        the moon over the valley of Aijalon.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the sun stood still and the moon stayed in place until the nation
        of Israel had defeated its enemies.Is this event not recorded in The Book
        of Jashar[[COMMENT(0)]]? The sun stayed in the middle of the sky, and it
        did not set as on a normal day.[[COMMENT(1)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '10:13a '
        content: Or <b>The Book of the Upright.</b>
      - number: '10:13b '
        content: Or <b>did not set for about a whole day.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'There has never been a day like this one before or since, when the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> answered such a prayer. Surely the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        fought for Israel that day!  '
      comments: []
    - title: Joshua Kills the Five Southern Kings
      content: 'Then Joshua and the Israelite army returned to their camp at Gilgal.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'During the battle the five kings escaped and hid in a cave at Makkedah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Joshua heard that they had been found, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "he issued this command: \u201CCover the opening of the cave with
        large rocks, and place guards at the entrance to keep the kings inside. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The rest of you continue chasing the enemy and cut them down from
        the rear. Don\u2019t give them a chance to get back to their towns, for the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God has given you victory over them.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Joshua and the Israelite army continued the slaughter and completely
        crushed the enemy. They totally wiped out the five armies except for a tiny
        remnant that managed to reach their fortified towns. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the Israelites returned safely to Joshua in the camp at Makkedah.
        After that, no one dared to speak even a word against Israel.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Joshua said, \u201CRemove the rocks covering the opening of
        the cave, and bring the five kings to me.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So they brought the five kings out of the cave\u2014the kings of
        Jerusalem, Hebron, Jarmuth, Lachish, and Eglon. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When they brought them out, Joshua told the commanders of his army,
        \u201CCome and put your feet on the kings\u2019 necks.\u201D And they did
        as they were told.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CDon\u2019t ever be afraid or discouraged,\u201D Joshua told
        his men. \u201CBe strong and courageous, for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        is going to do this to all of your enemies.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Joshua killed each of the five kings and impaled them on five
        sharpened poles, where they hung until evening.  '
      comments: []
    - title: Israel Destroys the Southern Towns
      content: 'As the sun was going down, Joshua gave instructions for the bodies
        of the kings to be taken down from the poles and thrown into the cave where
        they had been hiding. Then they covered the opening of the cave with a pile
        of large rocks, which remains to this very day.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'That same day Joshua captured and destroyed the town of Makkedah.
        He killed everyone in it, including the king, leaving no survivors. He destroyed
        them all, and he killed the king of Makkedah as he had killed the king of
        Jericho. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Joshua and the Israelites went to Libnah and attacked it. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'There, too, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> gave them the town and
        its king. He killed everyone in it, leaving no survivors. Then Joshua killed
        the king of Libnah as he had killed the king of Jericho.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'From Libnah, Joshua and the Israelites went to Lachish and attacked
        it. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Here again, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> gave them Lachish. Joshua
        took it on the second day and killed everyone in it, just as he had done
        at Libnah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "During the attack on Lachish, King Horam of Gezer arrived with his
        army to help defend the town. But Joshua\u2019s men killed him and his army,
        leaving no survivors.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Joshua and the Israelite army went on to Eglon and attacked
        it. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They captured it that day and killed everyone in it. He completely
        destroyed everyone, just as he had done at Lachish. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'From Eglon, Joshua and the Israelite army went up to Hebron and attacked
        it. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They captured the town and killed everyone in it, including its king,
        leaving no survivors. They did the same thing to all of its surrounding villages.
        And just as he had done at Eglon, he completely destroyed the entire population.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Joshua and the Israelites turned back and attacked Debir. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He captured the town, its king, and all of its surrounding villages.
        He completely destroyed everyone in it, leaving no survivors. He did to Debir
        and its king just what he had done to Hebron and to Libnah and its king.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Joshua conquered the whole region\u2014the kings and people of
        the hill country, the Negev, the western foothills,[[COMMENT(0)]] and the
        mountain slopes. He completely destroyed everyone in the land, leaving no
        survivors, just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of Israel, had
        commanded. "
      comments:
      - number: '10:40 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Shephelah.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Joshua slaughtered them from Kadesh-barnea to Gaza and from the region
        around the town of Goshen up to Gibeon. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Joshua conquered all these kings and their land in a single campaign,
        for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of Israel, was fighting for
        his people.  '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Israel Defeats the Northern Armies
      content: '  When King Jabin of Hazor heard what had happened, he sent messages
        to the following kings: King Jobab of Madon; the king of Shimron; the king
        of Acshaph; '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'all the kings of the northern hill country; the kings in the Jordan
        Valley south of Galilee[[COMMENT(0)]]; the kings in the Galilean foothills[[COMMENT(1)]];
        the kings of Naphoth-dor on the west; '
      comments:
      - number: '11:2a '
        content: Hebrew <b>in the Arabah south of Kinnereth.</b>
      - number: '11:2b '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Shephelah; </b>also in 11:16.
    - title: 
      content: 'the kings of Canaan, both east and west; the kings of the Amorites,
        the Hittites, the Perizzites, the Jebusites in the hill country, and the
        Hivites in the towns on the slopes of Mount Hermon in the land of Mizpah.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'All these kings came out to fight. Their combined armies formed a
        vast horde. And with all their horses and chariots, they covered the landscape
        like the sand on the seashore. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The kings joined forces and established their camp around the water
        near Merom to fight against Israel.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Joshua, \u201CDo not
        be afraid of them. By this time tomorrow I will hand all of them over to
        Israel as dead men. Then you must cripple their horses and burn their chariots.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Joshua and all his fighting men traveled to the water near Merom
        and attacked suddenly. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> gave them victory over their
        enemies. The Israelites chased them as far as Greater Sidon and Misrephoth-maim,
        and eastward into the valley of Mizpah, until not one enemy warrior was left
        alive. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Joshua crippled the horses and burned all the chariots, as the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had instructed.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Joshua then turned back and captured Hazor and killed its king. (Hazor
        had at one time been the capital of all these kingdoms.) '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The Israelites completely destroyed[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> every
        living thing in the city, leaving no survivors. Not a single person was spared.
        And then Joshua burned the city.</smallcaps>  '
      comments:
      - number: '11:11 '
        content: The Hebrew term used here refers to the complete consecration of
          things or people to the <span class="ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf">Lord</span>,
          either by destroying them or by giving them as an offering; also in 11:12,
          20, 21.
    - title: 
      content: 'Joshua slaughtered all the other kings and their people, completely
        destroying them, just as Moses, the servant of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        had commanded. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But the Israelites did not burn any of the towns built on mounds
        except Hazor, which Joshua burned. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And the Israelites took all the plunder and livestock of the ravaged
        towns for themselves. But they killed all the people, leaving no survivors. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had commanded his servant Moses,
        so Moses commanded Joshua. And Joshua did as he was told, carefully obeying
        all the commands that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had given to Moses.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Joshua conquered the entire region\u2014the hill country, the
        entire Negev, the whole area around the town of Goshen, the western foothills,
        the Jordan Valley,[[COMMENT(0)]] the mountains of Israel, and the Galilean
        foothills. "
      comments:
      - number: '11:16 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Shephelah, the Arabah.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'The Israelite territory now extended all the way from Mount Halak,
        which leads up to Seir in the south, as far north as Baal-gad at the foot
        of Mount Hermon in the valley of Lebanon. Joshua killed all the kings of
        those territories, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'waging war for a long time to accomplish this. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'No one in this region made peace with the Israelites except the Hivites
        of Gibeon. All the others were defeated. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> hardened their hearts and caused
        them to fight the Israelites. So they were completely destroyed without mercy,
        as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had commanded Moses.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'During this period Joshua destroyed all the descendants of Anak,
        who lived in the hill country of Hebron, Debir, Anab, and the entire hill
        country of Judah and Israel. He killed them all and completely destroyed
        their towns. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'None of the descendants of Anak were left in all the land of Israel,
        though some still remained in Gaza, Gath, and Ashdod.  '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Kings Defeated East of the Jordan
      content: '  These are the kings east of the Jordan River who had been killed
        by the Israelites and whose land was taken. Their territory extended from
        the Arnon Gorge to Mount Hermon and included all the land east of the Jordan
        Valley.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '12:1 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Arabah; </b>also in 12:3, 8.
    - title: 
      content: 'King Sihon of the Amorites, who lived in Heshbon, was defeated. His
        kingdom included Aroer, on the edge of the Arnon Gorge, and extended from
        the middle of the Arnon Gorge to the Jabbok River, which serves as a border
        for the Ammonites. This territory included the southern half of the territory
        of Gilead. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Sihon also controlled the Jordan Valley and regions to the east\u2014from
        as far north as the Sea of Galilee to as far south as the Dead Sea,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        including the road to Beth-jeshimoth and southward to the slopes of Pisgah.  "
      comments:
      - number: '12:3 '
        content: Hebrew <b>from the Sea of Kinnereth to the Sea of the Arabah, which
          is the Salt Sea.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'King Og of Bashan, the last of the Rephaites, lived at Ashtaroth
        and Edrei. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He ruled a territory stretching from Mount Hermon to Salecah in the
        north and to all of Bashan in the east, and westward to the borders of the
        kingdoms of Geshur and Maacah. This territory included the northern half
        of Gilead, as far as the boundary of King Sihon of Heshbon.  '
      comments: []
    - title: Kings Defeated West of the Jordan
      content: 'Moses, the servant of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, and the Israelites
        had destroyed the people of King Sihon and King Og. And Moses gave their
        land as a possession to the tribes of Reuben, Gad, and the half-tribe of
        Manasseh.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The following is a list of the kings that Joshua and the Israelite
        armies defeated on the west side of the Jordan, from Baal-gad in the valley
        of Lebanon to Mount Halak, which leads up to Seir. (Joshua gave this land
        to the tribes of Israel as their possession, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'including the hill country, the western foothills,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        the Jordan Valley, the mountain slopes, the Judean wilderness, and the Negev.
        The people who lived in this region were the Hittites, the Amorites, the
        Canaanites, the Perizzites, the Hivites, and the Jebusites.) These are the
        kings Israel defeated:  '
      comments:
      - number: '12:8 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Shephelah.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'The king of JerichoThe king of Ai, near Bethel  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The king of JerusalemThe king of Hebron  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The king of JarmuthThe king of Lachish  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The king of EglonThe king of Gezer  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The king of DebirThe king of Geder  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The king of HormahThe king of Arad  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The king of LibnahThe king of Adullam  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The king of MakkedahThe king of Bethel  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The king of TappuahThe king of Hepher  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The king of AphekThe king of Lasharon  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The king of MadonThe king of Hazor  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The king of Shimron-meronThe king of Acshaph  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The king of TaanachThe king of Megiddo  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The king of KedeshThe king of Jokneam in Carmel  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The king of Dor in the town of Naphoth-dor[[COMMENT(0)]]The king
        of Goyim in Gilgal[[COMMENT(1)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '12:23a '
        content: Hebrew <b>Naphath-dor, </b>a variant spelling of Naphoth-dor.
      - number: '12:23b '
        content: Greek version reads <b>Goyim in Galilee.</b>
  - verses:
    - title: The Land Yet to Be Conquered
      content: "  When Joshua was an old man, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said
        to him, \u201CYou are growing old, and much land remains to be conquered. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'This is the territory that remains: all the regions of the Philistines
        and the Geshurites, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and the larger territory of the Canaanites, extending from the stream
        of Shihor on the border of Egypt, northward to the boundary of Ekron. It
        includes the territory of the five Philistine rulers of Gaza, Ashdod, Ashkelon,
        Gath, and Ekron. The land of the Avvites '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'in the south also remains to be conquered. In the north, the following
        area has not yet been conquered: all the land of the Canaanites, including
        Mearah (which belongs to the Sidonians), stretching northward to Aphek on
        the border of the Amorites; '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'the land of the Gebalites and all of the Lebanon mountain area to
        the east, from Baal-gad below Mount Hermon to Lebo-hamath; '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "and all the hill country from Lebanon to Misrephoth-maim, including
        all the land of the Sidonians.\u201CI myself will drive these people out
        of the land ahead of the Israelites. So be sure to give this land to Israel
        as a special possession, just as I have commanded you. "
      comments: []
    - title: The Land Divided East of the Jordan
      content: "Include all this territory as Israel\u2019s possession when you divide
        this land among the nine tribes and the half-tribe of Manasseh.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Half the tribe of Manasseh and the tribes of Reuben and Gad had already
        received their grants of land on the east side of the Jordan, for Moses,
        the servant of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, had previously assigned this
        land to them.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Their territory extended from Aroer on the edge of the Arnon Gorge
        (including the town in the middle of the gorge) to the plain beyond Medeba,
        as far as Dibon. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'It also included all the towns of King Sihon of the Amorites, who
        had reigned in Heshbon, and extended as far as the borders of Ammon. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'It included Gilead, the territory of the kingdoms of Geshur and Maacah,
        all of Mount Hermon, all of Bashan as far as Salecah, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and all the territory of King Og of Bashan, who had reigned in Ashtaroth
        and Edrei. King Og was the last of the Rephaites, for Moses had attacked
        them and driven them out. '
      comments: []
    - title: An Allotment for the Tribe of Levi
      content: 'But the Israelites failed to drive out the people of Geshur and Maacah,
        so they continue to live among the Israelites to this day.  '
      comments: []
    - title: The Land Given to the Tribe of Reuben
      content: 'Moses did not assign any allotment of land to the tribe of Levi.
        Instead, as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had promised them, their allotment
        came from the offerings burned on the altar to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of Israel.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Moses had assigned the following area to the clans of the tribe of
        Reuben.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Their territory extended from Aroer on the edge of the Arnon Gorge
        (including the town in the middle of the gorge) to the plain beyond Medeba. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "It included Heshbon and the other towns on the plain\u2014Dibon,
        Bamoth-baal, Beth-baal-meon, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Jahaz, Kedemoth, Mephaath, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Kiriathaim, Sibmah, Zereth-shahar on the hill above the valley, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Beth-peor, the slopes of Pisgah, and Beth-jeshimoth.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The land of Reuben also included all the towns of the plain and the
        entire kingdom of Sihon. Sihon was the Amorite king who had reigned in Heshbon
        and was killed by Moses along with the leaders of Midian\u2014Evi, Rekem,
        Zur, Hur, and Reba\u2014princes living in the region who were allied with
        Sihon. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The Israelites had also killed Balaam son of Beor, who used magic
        to tell the future. '
      comments: []
    - title: The Land Given to the Tribe of Gad
      content: 'The Jordan River marked the western boundary for the tribe of Reuben.
        The towns and their surrounding villages in this area were given as a homeland
        to the clans of the tribe of Reuben.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Moses had assigned the following area to the clans of the tribe of
        Gad.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Their territory included Jazer, all the towns of Gilead, and half
        of the land of Ammon, as far as the town of Aroer just west of[[COMMENT(0)]]
        Rabbah. '
      comments:
      - number: '13:25 '
        content: Hebrew <b>in front of.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'It extended from Heshbon to Ramath-mizpeh and Betonim, and from Mahanaim
        to the territory of Lo-debar.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '13:26 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Li-debir, </b>apparently a variant spelling of Lo-debar
          (compare 2 Sam 9:4; 17:27; Amos 6:13).
    - title: 
      content: 'In the valley were Beth-haram, Beth-nimrah, Succoth, Zaphon, and
        the rest of the kingdom of King Sihon of Heshbon. The western boundary ran
        along the Jordan River, extended as far north as the tip of the Sea of Galilee,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        and then turned eastward. '
      comments:
      - number: '13:27 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Sea of Kinnereth.</b>
    - title: The Land Given to the Half-Tribe of Manasseh
      content: 'The towns and their surrounding villages in this area were given
        as a homeland to the clans of the tribe of Gad.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Moses had assigned the following area to the clans of the half-tribe
        of Manasseh.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Their territory extended from Mahanaim, including all of Bashan,
        all the former kingdom of King Og, and the sixty towns of Jair in Bashan. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "It also included half of Gilead and King Og\u2019s royal cities of
        Ashtaroth and Edrei. All this was given to the clans of the descendants of
        Makir, who was Manasseh\u2019s son.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'These are the allotments Moses had made while he was on the plains
        of Moab, across the Jordan River, east of Jericho. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Land Divided West of the Jordan
      content: '  The remaining tribes of Israel received land in Canaan as allotted
        by Eleazar the priest, Joshua son of Nun, and the tribal leaders. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "These nine and a half tribes received their grants of land by means
        of sacred lots, in accordance with the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        command through Moses. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Moses had already given a grant of land to the two and a half tribes
        on the east side of the Jordan River, but he had given the Levites no such
        allotment. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The descendants of Joseph had become two separate tribes\u2014Manasseh
        and Ephraim. And the Levites were given no land at all, only towns to live
        in with surrounding pasturelands for their livestock and all their possessions. "
      comments: []
    - title: Caleb Requests His Land
      content: "So the land was distributed in strict accordance with the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        commands to Moses.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "A delegation from the tribe of Judah, led by Caleb son of Jephunneh
        the Kenizzite, came to Joshua at Gilgal. Caleb said to Joshua, \u201CRemember
        what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, the man of God, about
        you and me when we were at Kadesh-barnea. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I was forty years old when Moses, the servant of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        sent me from Kadesh-barnea to explore the land of Canaan. I returned and
        gave an honest report, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'but my brothers who went with me frightened the people from entering
        the Promised Land. For my part, I wholeheartedly followed the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        my God. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So that day Moses solemnly promised me, \u2018The land of Canaan
        on which you were just walking will be your grant of land and that of your
        descendants forever, because you wholeheartedly followed the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        my God.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNow, as you can see, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has kept
        me alive and well as he promised for all these forty-five years since Moses
        made this promise\u2014even while Israel wandered in the wilderness. Today
        I am eighty-five years old. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I am as strong now as I was when Moses sent me on that journey, and
        I can still travel and fight as well as I could then. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So give me the hill country that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        promised me. You will remember that as scouts we found the descendants of
        Anak living there in great, walled towns. But if the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        is with me, I will drive them out of the land, just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        said.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Joshua blessed Caleb son of Jephunneh and gave Hebron to him as
        his portion of land. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Hebron still belongs to the descendants of Caleb son of Jephunneh
        the Kenizzite because he wholeheartedly followed the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of Israel. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Land Given to the Tribe of Judah
      content: '  The allotment for the clans of the tribe of Judah reached southward
        to the border of Edom, as far south as the wilderness of Zin.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The southern boundary began at the south bay of the Dead Sea,[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '15:2 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Salt Sea; </b>also in 15:5.
    - title: 
      content: 'ran south of Scorpion Pass[[COMMENT(0)]] into the wilderness of Zin,
        and then went south of Kadesh-barnea to Hezron. Then it went up to Addar,
        where it turned toward Karka. '
      comments:
      - number: '15:3 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Akrabbim.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'From there it passed to Azmon until it finally reached the Brook
        of Egypt, which it followed to the Mediterranean Sea.[[COMMENT(0)]] This
        was their[[COMMENT(1)]] southern boundary.  '
      comments:
      - number: '15:4a '
        content: Hebrew <b>the sea; </b>also in 15:11.
      - number: '15:4b '
        content: Hebrew <b>your.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'The eastern boundary extended along the Dead Sea to the mouth of
        the Jordan River.The northern boundary began at the bay where the Jordan
        River empties into the Dead Sea, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "went up from there to Beth-hoglah, then proceeded north of Beth-arabah
        to the Stone of Bohan. (Bohan was Reuben\u2019s son.) "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'From that point it went through the valley of Achor to Debir, turning
        north toward Gilgal, which is across from the slopes of Adummim on the south
        side of the valley. From there the boundary extended to the springs at En-shemesh
        and on to En-rogel. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The boundary then passed through the valley of Ben-Hinnom, along
        the southern slopes of the Jebusites, where the city of Jerusalem is located.
        Then it went west to the top of the mountain above the valley of Hinnom,
        and on up to the northern end of the valley of Rephaim. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'From there the boundary extended from the top of the mountain to
        the spring at the waters of Nephtoah,[[COMMENT(0)]] and from there to the
        towns on Mount Ephron. Then it turned toward Baalah (that is, Kiriath-jearim). '
      comments:
      - number: '15:9 '
        content: Or <b>the spring at Me-nephtoah.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'The boundary circled west of Baalah to Mount Seir, passed along to
        the town of Kesalon on the northern slope of Mount Jearim, and went down
        to Beth-shemesh and on to Timnah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The boundary then proceeded to the slope of the hill north of Ekron,
        where it turned toward Shikkeron and Mount Baalah. It passed Jabneel and
        ended at the Mediterranean Sea.  '
      comments: []
    - title: The Land Given to Caleb
      content: 'The western boundary was the shoreline of the Mediterranean Sea.[[COMMENT(0)]]These
        are the boundaries for the clans of the tribe of Judah.  '
      comments:
      - number: '15:12 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Great Sea; </b>also in 15:47.
    - title: 
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> commanded Joshua to assign some of
        Judah\u2019s territory to Caleb son of Jephunneh. So Caleb was given the
        town of Kiriath-arba (that is, Hebron), which had been named after Anak\u2019s
        ancestor. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Caleb drove out the three groups of Anakites\u2014the descendants
        of Sheshai, Ahiman, and Talmai, the sons of Anak.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'From there he went to fight against the people living in the town
        of Debir (formerly called Kiriath-sepher). '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Caleb said, \u201CI will give my daughter Acsah in marriage to the
        one who attacks and captures Kiriath-sepher.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Othniel, the son of Caleb\u2019s brother Kenaz, was the one who conquered
        it, so Acsah became Othniel\u2019s wife.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When Acsah married Othniel, she urged him[[COMMENT(0)]] to ask her
        father for a field. As she got down off her donkey, Caleb asked her, \u201CWhat\u2019s
        the matter?\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '15:18 '
        content: Some Greek manuscripts read <b>he urged her.</b>
    - title: The Towns Allotted to Judah
      content: "She said, \u201CGive me another gift. You have already given me land
        in the Negev; now please give me springs of water, too.\u201D So Caleb gave
        her the upper and lower springs.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'This was the homeland allocated to the clans of the tribe of Judah.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The towns of Judah situated along the borders of Edom in the extreme
        south were Kabzeel, Eder, Jagur, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Kinah, Dimonah, Adadah, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Kedesh, Hazor, Ithnan, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Ziph, Telem, Bealoth, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Hazor-hadattah, Kerioth-hezron (that is, Hazor), '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Amam, Shema, Moladah, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Hazar-gaddah, Heshmon, Beth-pelet, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Hazar-shual, Beersheba, Biziothiah, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Baalah, Iim, Ezem, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Eltolad, Kesil, Hormah, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Ziklag, Madmannah, Sansannah, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Lebaoth, Shilhim, Ain, and Rimmon\u2014twenty-nine towns with their
        surrounding villages.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The following towns situated in the western foothills[[COMMENT(0)]]
        were also given to Judah: Eshtaol, Zorah, Ashnah, '
      comments:
      - number: '15:33 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Shephelah.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Zanoah, En-gannim, Tappuah, Enam, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Jarmuth, Adullam, Socoh, Azekah, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Shaaraim, Adithaim, Gederah, and Gederothaim\u2014fourteen towns
        with their surrounding villages.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Also included were Zenan, Hadashah, Migdal-gad, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Dilean, Mizpeh, Joktheel, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Lachish, Bozkath, Eglon, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Cabbon, Lahmam, Kitlish, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Gederoth, Beth-dagon, Naamah, and Makkedah\u2014sixteen towns with
        their surrounding villages.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Besides these, there were Libnah, Ether, Ashan, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Iphtah, Ashnah, Nezib, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Keilah, Aczib, and Mareshah\u2014nine towns with their surrounding
        villages.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The territory of the tribe of Judah also included Ekron and its surrounding
        settlements and villages. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'From Ekron the boundary extended west and included the towns near
        Ashdod with their surrounding villages. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'It also included Ashdod with its surrounding settlements and villages
        and Gaza with its settlements and villages, as far as the Brook of Egypt
        and along the coast of the Mediterranean Sea.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Judah also received the following towns in the hill country: Shamir,
        Jattir, Socoh, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Dannah, Kiriath-sannah (that is, Debir), '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Anab, Eshtemoh, Anim, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Goshen, Holon, and Giloh\u2014eleven towns with their surrounding
        villages.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Also included were the towns of Arab, Dumah, Eshan, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Janim, Beth-tappuah, Aphekah, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Humtah, Kiriath-arba (that is, Hebron), and Zior\u2014nine towns
        with their surrounding villages.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Besides these, there were Maon, Carmel, Ziph, Juttah, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Jezreel, Jokdeam, Zanoah, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Kain, Gibeah, and Timnah\u2014ten towns with their surrounding villages.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'In addition, there were Halhul, Beth-zur, Gedor, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Maarath, Beth-anoth, and Eltekon\u2014six towns with their surrounding
        villages.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "There were also Kiriath-baal (that is, Kiriath-jearim) and Rabbah\u2014two
        towns with their surrounding villages.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'In the wilderness there were the towns of Beth-arabah, Middin, Secacah, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Nibshan, the City of Salt, and En-gedi\u2014six towns with their
        surrounding villages.  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Land Given to Ephraim and West Manasseh
      content: '  The allotment for the descendants of Joseph extended from the Jordan
        River near Jericho, east of the springs of Jericho, through the wilderness
        and into the hill country of Bethel. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'From Bethel (that is, Luz)[[COMMENT(0)]] it ran over to Ataroth in
        the territory of the Arkites. '
      comments:
      - number: '16:2 '
        content: As in Greek version (also see 18:13); Hebrew reads <b>From Bethel
          to Luz.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Then it descended westward to the territory of the Japhletites as
        far as Lower Beth-horon, then to Gezer and over to the Mediterranean Sea.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '16:3 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the sea; </b>also in 16:6, 8.
    - title: The Land Given to Ephraim
      content: "This was the homeland allocated to the families of Joseph\u2019s
        sons, Manasseh and Ephraim.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The following territory was given to the clans of the tribe of Ephraim.The
        boundary of their homeland began at Ataroth-addar in the east. From there
        it ran to Upper Beth-horon, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'then on to the Mediterranean Sea. From Micmethath on the north, the
        boundary curved eastward past Taanath-shiloh to the east of Janoah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'From Janoah it turned southward to Ataroth and Naarah, touched Jericho,
        and ended at the Jordan River. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'From Tappuah the boundary extended westward, following the Kanah
        Ravine to the Mediterranean Sea. This is the homeland allocated to the clans
        of the tribe of Ephraim.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'In addition, some towns with their surrounding villages in the territory
        allocated to the half-tribe of Manasseh were set aside for the tribe of Ephraim. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Land Given to West Manasseh
      content: "  The next allotment of land was given to the half-tribe of Manasseh,
        the descendants of Joseph\u2019s older son. Makir, the firstborn son of Manasseh,
        was the father of Gilead. Because his descendants were experienced soldiers,
        the regions of Gilead and Bashan on the east side of the Jordan had already
        been given to them. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the allotment on the west side of the Jordan was for the remaining
        families within the clans of the tribe of Manasseh: Abiezer, Helek, Asriel,
        Shechem, Hepher, and Shemida. These clans represent the male descendants
        of Manasseh son of Joseph.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'However, Zelophehad, a descendant of Hepher son of Gilead, son of
        Makir, son of Manasseh, had no sons. He had only daughters, whose names were
        Mahlah, Noah, Hoglah, Milcah, and Tirzah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "These women came to Eleazar the priest, Joshua son of Nun, and the
        Israelite leaders and said, \u201CThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> commanded
        Moses to give us a grant of land along with the men of our tribe.\u201DSo
        Joshua gave them a grant of land along with their uncles, as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had commanded. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "As a result, Manasseh\u2019s total allocation came to ten parcels
        of land, in addition to the land of Gilead and Bashan across the Jordan River, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'because the female descendants of Manasseh received a grant of land
        along with the male descendants. (The land of Gilead was given to the rest
        of the male descendants of Manasseh.)  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The boundary of the tribe of Manasseh extended from the border of
        Asher to Micmethath, near Shechem. Then the boundary went south from Micmethath
        to the settlement near the spring of Tappuah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The land surrounding Tappuah belonged to Manasseh, but the town of
        Tappuah itself, on the border of Manasseh\u2019s territory, belonged to the
        tribe of Ephraim. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "From the spring of Tappuah, the boundary of Manasseh followed the
        Kanah Ravine to the Mediterranean Sea.[[COMMENT(0)]] Several towns south
        of the ravine were inside Manasseh\u2019s territory, but they actually belonged
        to the tribe of Ephraim. "
      comments:
      - number: '17:9 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the sea; </b>also in 17:10.
    - title: 
      content: "In general, however, the land south of the ravine belonged to Ephraim,
        and the land north of the ravine belonged to Manasseh. Manasseh\u2019s boundary
        ran along the northern side of the ravine and ended at the Mediterranean
        Sea. North of Manasseh was the territory of Asher, and to the east was the
        territory of Issachar.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The following towns within the territory of Issachar and Asher, however,
        were given to Manasseh: Beth-shan,[[COMMENT(0)]] Ibleam, Dor (that is, Naphoth-dor),[[COMMENT(1)]]
        Endor, Taanach, and Megiddo, each with their surrounding settlements.  '
      comments:
      - number: '17:11a '
        content: Hebrew <b>Beth-shean, </b>a variant spelling of Beth-shan; also
          in 17:16.
      - number: '17:11b '
        content: The meaning of the Hebrew here is uncertain.
    - title: 
      content: 'But the descendants of Manasseh were unable to occupy these towns
        because the Canaanites were determined to stay in that region. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Later, however, when the Israelites became strong enough, they forced
        the Canaanites to work as slaves. But they did not drive them out of the
        land.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The descendants of Joseph came to Joshua and asked, \u201CWhy have
        you given us only one portion of land as our homeland when the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has blessed us with so many people?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Joshua replied, \u201CIf there are so many of you, and if the hill
        country of Ephraim is not large enough for you, clear out land for yourselves
        in the forest where the Perizzites and Rephaites live.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The descendants of Joseph responded, \u201CIt\u2019s true that the
        hill country is not large enough for us. But all the Canaanites in the lowlands
        have iron chariots, both those in Beth-shan and its surrounding settlements
        and those in the valley of Jezreel. They are too strong for us.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Joshua said to the tribes of Ephraim and Manasseh, the descendants
        of Joseph, \u201CSince you are so large and strong, you will be given more
        than one portion. "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Allotments of the Remaining Land
      content: '  Now that the land was under Israelite control, the entire community
        of Israel gathered at Shiloh and set up the Tabernacle.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '18:1 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Tent of Meeting.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'But there remained seven tribes who had not yet been allotted their
        grants of land.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Joshua asked them, \u201CHow long are you going to wait before
        taking possession of the remaining land the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of your ancestors, has given to you? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Select three men from each tribe, and I will send them out to explore
        the land and map it out. They will then return to me with a written report
        of their proposed divisions of their new homeland. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Let them divide the land into seven sections, excluding Judah\u2019s
        territory in the south and Joseph\u2019s territory in the north. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And when you record the seven divisions of the land and bring them
        to me, I will cast sacred lots in the presence of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        our God to assign land to each tribe.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThe Levites, however, will not receive any allotment of land.
        Their role as priests of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> is their allotment.
        And the tribes of Gad, Reuben, and the half-tribe of Manasseh won\u2019t
        receive any more land, for they have already received their grant of land,
        which Moses, the servant of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, gave them on
        the east side of the Jordan River.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "As the men started on their way to map out the land, Joshua commanded
        them, \u201CGo and explore the land and write a description of it. Then return
        to me, and I will assign the land to the tribes by casting sacred lots here
        in the presence of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> at Shiloh.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The men did as they were told and mapped the entire territory into
        seven sections, listing the towns in each section. They made a written record
        and then returned to Joshua in the camp at Shiloh. '
      comments: []
    - title: The Land Given to Benjamin
      content: 'And there at Shiloh, Joshua cast sacred lots in the presence of the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> to determine which tribe should have each section.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The first allotment of land went to the clans of the tribe of Benjamin.
        It lay between the territory assigned to the tribes of Judah and Joseph.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The northern boundary of Benjamin\u2019s land began at the Jordan
        River, went north of the slope of Jericho, then west through the hill country
        and the wilderness of Beth-aven. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'From there the boundary went south to Luz (that is, Bethel) and proceeded
        down to Ataroth-addar on the hill that lies south of Lower Beth-horon.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The boundary then made a turn and swung south along the western edge
        of the hill facing Beth-horon, ending at the village of Kiriath-baal (that
        is, Kiriath-jearim), a town belonging to the tribe of Judah. This was the
        western boundary.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The southern boundary began at the outskirts of Kiriath-jearim. From
        that western point it ran[[COMMENT(0)]] to the spring at the waters of Nephtoah,[[COMMENT(1)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '18:15a '
        content: Or <b>From there it went to Mozah. </b>The meaning of the Hebrew
          is uncertain.
      - number: '18:15b '
        content: Or <b>the spring at Me-nephtoah.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'and down to the base of the mountain beside the valley of Ben-Hinnom,
        at the northern end of the valley of Rephaim. From there it went down the
        valley of Hinnom, crossing south of the slope where the Jebusites lived,
        and continued down to En-rogel. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "From En-rogel the boundary proceeded in a northerly direction and
        came to En-shemesh and on to Geliloth (which is across from the slopes of
        Adummim). Then it went down to the Stone of Bohan. (Bohan was Reuben\u2019s
        son.) "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'From there it passed along the north side of the slope overlooking
        the Jordan Valley.[[COMMENT(0)]] The border then went down into the valley, '
      comments:
      - number: '18:18 '
        content: Hebrew <b>overlooking the Arabah, </b>or <b>overlooking Beth-arabah.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'ran past the north slope of Beth-hoglah, and ended at the north bay
        of the Dead Sea,[[COMMENT(0)]] which is the southern end of the Jordan River.
        This was the southern boundary.  '
      comments:
      - number: '18:19 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Salt Sea.</b>
    - title: The Towns Given to Benjamin
      content: 'The eastern boundary was the Jordan River.These were the boundaries
        of the homeland allocated to the clans of the tribe of Benjamin.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'These were the towns given to the clans of the tribe of Benjamin.Jericho,
        Beth-hoglah, Emek-keziz, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Beth-arabah, Zemaraim, Bethel, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Avvim, Parah, Ophrah, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Kephar-ammoni, Ophni, and Geba\u2014twelve towns with their surrounding
        villages. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Also Gibeon, Ramah, Beeroth, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Mizpah, Kephirah, Mozah, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Rekem, Irpeel, Taralah, '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Land Given to Simeon
      content: "  The second allotment of land went to the clans of the tribe of
        Simeon. Their homeland was surrounded by Judah\u2019s territory.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Simeon\u2019s homeland included Beersheba, Sheba, Moladah, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Hazar-shual, Balah, Ezem, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Eltolad, Bethul, Hormah, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Ziklag, Beth-marcaboth, Hazar-susah, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Beth-lebaoth, and Sharuhen\u2014thirteen towns with their surrounding
        villages. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "It also included Ain, Rimmon, Ether, and Ashan\u2014four towns with
        their villages, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'including all the surrounding villages as far south as Baalath-beer
        (also known as Ramah of the Negev).This was the homeland allocated to the
        clans of the tribe of Simeon. '
      comments: []
    - title: The Land Given to Zebulun
      content: "Their allocation of land came from part of what had been given to
        Judah because Judah\u2019s territory was too large for them. So the tribe
        of Simeon received an allocation within the territory of Judah.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The third allotment of land went to the clans of the tribe of Zebulun.The
        boundary of Zebulun\u2019s homeland started at Sarid. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'From there it went west, going past Maralah, touching Dabbesheth,
        and proceeding to the brook east of Jokneam. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'In the other direction, the boundary went east from Sarid to the
        border of Kisloth-tabor, and from there to Daberath and up to Japhia. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then it continued east to Gath-hepher, Eth-kazin, and Rimmon and
        turned toward Neah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The northern boundary of Zebulun passed Hannathon and ended at the
        valley of Iphtah-el. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The towns in these areas included Kattath, Nahalal, Shimron, Idalah,
        and Bethlehem\u2014twelve towns with their surrounding villages.  "
      comments: []
    - title: The Land Given to Issachar
      content: 'The homeland allocated to the clans of the tribe of Zebulun included
        these towns and their surrounding villages.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The fourth allotment of land went to the clans of the tribe of Issachar.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Its boundaries included the following towns: Jezreel, Kesulloth,
        Shunem, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Hapharaim, Shion, Anaharath, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Rabbith, Kishion, Ebez, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Remeth, En-gannim, En-haddah, and Beth-pazzez. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The boundary also touched Tabor, Shahazumah, and Beth-shemesh, ending
        at the Jordan River\u2014sixteen towns with their surrounding villages.  "
      comments: []
    - title: The Land Given to Asher
      content: 'The homeland allocated to the clans of the tribe of Issachar included
        these towns and their surrounding villages.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The fifth allotment of land went to the clans of the tribe of Asher.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Its boundaries included these towns: Helkath, Hali, Beten, Acshaph, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Allammelech, Amad, and Mishal. The boundary on the west touched Carmel
        and Shihor-libnath, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'then it turned east toward Beth-dagon, and ran as far as Zebulun
        in the valley of Iphtah-el, going north to Beth-emek and Neiel. It then continued
        north to Cabul, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Abdon,[[COMMENT(0)]] Rehob, Hammon, Kanah, and as far as Greater
        Sidon. '
      comments:
      - number: '19:28 '
        content: As in some Hebrew manuscripts (see also 21:30); most Hebrew manuscripts
          read <b>Ebron.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the boundary turned toward Ramah and the fortress of Tyre, where
        it turned toward Hosah and came to the Mediterranean Sea.[[COMMENT(0)]] The
        territory also included Mehebel, Aczib, '
      comments:
      - number: '19:29 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the sea.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "Ummah, Aphek, and Rehob\u2014twenty-two towns with their surrounding
        villages.  "
      comments: []
    - title: The Land Given to Naphtali
      content: 'The homeland allocated to the clans of the tribe of Asher included
        these towns and their surrounding villages.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The sixth allotment of land went to the clans of the tribe of Naphtali.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Its boundary ran from Heleph, from the oak at Zaanannim, and extended
        across to Adami-nekeb, Jabneel, and as far as Lakkum, ending at the Jordan
        River. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The western boundary ran past Aznoth-tabor, then to Hukkok, and touched
        the border of Zebulun in the south, the border of Asher on the west, and
        the Jordan River[[COMMENT(0)]] on the east. '
      comments:
      - number: '19:34 '
        content: Hebrew <b>and Judah at the Jordan River.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'The fortified towns included in this territory were Ziddim, Zer,
        Hammath, Rakkath, Kinnereth, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Adamah, Ramah, Hazor, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Kedesh, Edrei, En-hazor, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Yiron, Migdal-el, Horem, Beth-anath, and Beth-shemesh\u2014nineteen
        towns with their surrounding villages.  "
      comments: []
    - title: The Land Given to Dan
      content: 'The homeland allocated to the clans of the tribe of Naphtali included
        these towns and their surrounding villages.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The seventh allotment of land went to the clans of the tribe of Dan.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The land allocated as their homeland included the following towns:
        Zorah, Eshtaol, Ir-shemesh, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Shaalabbin, Aijalon, Ithlah, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Elon, Timnah, Ekron, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Eltekeh, Gibbethon, Baalath, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Jehud, Bene-berak, Gath-rimmon, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Me-jarkon, Rakkon, and the territory across from Joppa.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But the tribe of Dan had trouble taking possession of their land,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        so they attacked the town of Laish.[[COMMENT(1)]] They captured it, slaughtered
        its people, and settled there. They renamed the town Dan after their ancestor.  '
      comments:
      - number: '19:47a '
        content: Or <b>had trouble holding on to their land.</b>
      - number: '19:47b '
        content: Hebrew <b>Leshem, </b>a variant spelling of Laish.
    - title: The Land Given to Joshua
      content: 'The homeland allocated to the clans of the tribe of Dan included
        these towns and their surrounding villages.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After all the land was divided among the tribes, the Israelites gave
        a piece of land to Joshua as his allocation. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had said he could have any town
        he wanted. He chose Timnath-serah in the hill country of Ephraim. He rebuilt
        the town and lived there.  '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Cities of Refuge
      content: '  The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Joshua, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNow tell the Israelites to designate the cities of refuge,
        as I instructed Moses. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Anyone who kills another person accidentally and unintentionally
        can run to one of these cities; they will be places of refuge from relatives
        seeking revenge for the person who was killed.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CUpon reaching one of these cities, the one who caused the death
        will appear before the elders at the city gate and present his case. They
        must allow him to enter the city and give him a place to live among them. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'If the relatives of the victim come to avenge the killing, the leaders
        must not release the slayer to them, for he killed the other person unintentionally
        and without previous hostility. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the slayer must stay in that city and be tried by the local assembly,
        which will render a judgment. And he must continue to live in that city until
        the death of the high priest who was in office at the time of the accident.
        After that, he is free to return to his own home in the town from which he
        fled.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The following cities were designated as cities of refuge: Kedesh
        of Galilee, in the hill country of Naphtali; Shechem, in the hill country
        of Ephraim; and Kiriath-arba (that is, Hebron), in the hill country of Judah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'On the east side of the Jordan River, across from Jericho, the following
        cities were designated: Bezer, in the wilderness plain of the tribe of Reuben;
        Ramoth in Gilead, in the territory of the tribe of Gad; and Golan in Bashan,
        in the land of the tribe of Manasseh. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Towns Given to the Levites
      content: '  Then the leaders of the tribe of Levi came to consult with Eleazar
        the priest, Joshua son of Nun, and the leaders of the other tribes of Israel. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They came to them at Shiloh in the land of Canaan and said, \u201CThe
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> commanded Moses to give us towns to live in and
        pasturelands for our livestock.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So by the command of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> the people of
        Israel gave the Levites the following towns and pasturelands out of their
        own grants of land.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The descendants of Aaron, who were members of the Kohathite clan
        within the tribe of Levi, were allotted thirteen towns that were originally
        assigned to the tribes of Judah, Simeon, and Benjamin. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The other families of the Kohathite clan were allotted ten towns
        from the tribes of Ephraim, Dan, and the half-tribe of Manasseh.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The clan of Gershon was allotted thirteen towns from the tribes of
        Issachar, Asher, Naphtali, and the half-tribe of Manasseh in Bashan.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The clan of Merari was allotted twelve towns from the tribes of Reuben,
        Gad, and Zebulun.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So the Israelites obeyed the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s command
        to Moses and assigned these towns and pasturelands to the Levites by casting
        sacred lots.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The Israelites gave the following towns from the tribes of Judah
        and Simeon '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'to the descendants of Aaron, who were members of the Kohathite clan
        within the tribe of Levi, since the sacred lot fell to them first: '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Kiriath-arba (that is, Hebron), in the hill country of Judah, along
        with its surrounding pasturelands. (Arba was an ancestor of Anak.) '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But the open fields beyond the town and the surrounding villages
        were given to Caleb son of Jephunneh as his possession.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The following towns with their pasturelands were given to the descendants
        of Aaron the priest: Hebron (a city of refuge for those who accidentally
        killed someone), Libnah, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Jattir, Eshtemoa, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Holon, Debir, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Ain, Juttah, and Beth-shemesh\u2014nine towns from these two tribes.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'From the tribe of Benjamin the priests were given the following towns
        with their pasturelands: Gibeon, Geba, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Anathoth, and Almon\u2014four towns. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So in all, thirteen towns with their pasturelands were given to the
        priests, the descendants of Aaron.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The rest of the Kohathite clan from the tribe of Levi was allotted
        the following towns and pasturelands from the tribe of Ephraim: '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Shechem in the hill country of Ephraim (a city of refuge for those
        who accidentally killed someone), Gezer, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Kibzaim, and Beth-horon\u2014four towns.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The following towns and pasturelands were allotted to the priests
        from the tribe of Dan: Eltekeh, Gibbethon, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Aijalon, and Gath-rimmon\u2014four towns.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The half-tribe of Manasseh allotted the following towns with their
        pasturelands to the priests: Taanach and Gath-rimmon\u2014two towns. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So in all, ten towns with their pasturelands were given to the rest
        of the Kohathite clan.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The descendants of Gershon, another clan within the tribe of Levi,
        received the following towns with their pasturelands from the half-tribe
        of Manasseh: Golan in Bashan (a city of refuge for those who accidentally
        killed someone) and Be-eshterah\u2014two towns.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'From the tribe of Issachar they received the following towns with
        their pasturelands: Kishion, Daberath, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Jarmuth, and En-gannim\u2014four towns.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'From the tribe of Asher they received the following towns with their
        pasturelands: Mishal, Abdon, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Helkath, and Rehob\u2014four towns.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "From the tribe of Naphtali they received the following towns with
        their pasturelands: Kedesh in Galilee (a city of refuge for those who accidentally
        killed someone), Hammoth-dor, and Kartan\u2014three towns. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So in all, thirteen towns with their pasturelands were allotted to
        the clan of Gershon.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The rest of the Levites\u2014the Merari clan\u2014were given the
        following towns with their pasturelands from the tribe of Zebulun: Jokneam,
        Kartah, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Dimnah, and Nahalal\u2014four towns.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'From the tribe of Reuben they received the following towns with their
        pasturelands: Bezer, Jahaz,[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '21:36 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Jahzah, </b>a variant spelling of Jahaz.
    - title: 
      content: "Kedemoth, and Mephaath\u2014four towns.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'From the tribe of Gad they received the following towns with their
        pasturelands: Ramoth in Gilead (a city of refuge for those who accidentally
        killed someone), Mahanaim, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Heshbon, and Jazer\u2014four towns. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So in all, twelve towns were allotted to the clan of Merari.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The total number of towns and pasturelands within Israelite territory
        given to the Levites came to forty-eight. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Every one of these towns had pasturelands surrounding it.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> gave to Israel all the land he
        had sworn to give their ancestors, and they took possession of it and settled
        there. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> gave them rest on every side,
        just as he had solemnly promised their ancestors. None of their enemies could
        stand against them, for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> helped them conquer
        all their enemies. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Eastern Tribes Return Home
      content: '  Then Joshua called together the tribes of Reuben, Gad, and the
        half-tribe of Manasseh. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He told them, \u201CYou have done as Moses, the servant of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        commanded you, and you have obeyed every order I have given you. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'During all this time you have not deserted the other tribes. You
        have been careful to obey the commands of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        your God right up to the present day. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And now the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God has given the other
        tribes rest, as he promised them. So go back home to the land that Moses,
        the servant of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, gave you as your possession
        on the east side of the Jordan River. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But be very careful to obey all the commands and the instructions
        that Moses gave to you. Love the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God, walk
        in all his ways, obey his commands, hold firmly to him, and serve him with
        all your heart and all your soul.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Joshua blessed them and sent them away, and they went home.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Moses had given the land of Bashan, east of the Jordan River, to
        the half-tribe of Manasseh. (The other half of the tribe was given land west
        of the Jordan.) As Joshua sent them away and blessed them, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "he said to them, \u201CGo back to your homes with the great wealth
        you have taken from your enemies\u2014the vast herds of livestock, the silver,
        gold, bronze, and iron, and the large supply of clothing. Share the plunder
        with your relatives.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: The Eastern Tribes Build an Altar
      content: "So the men of Reuben, Gad, and the half-tribe of Manasseh left the
        rest of Israel at Shiloh in the land of Canaan. They started the journey
        back to their own land of Gilead, the territory that belonged to them according
        to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s command through Moses.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But while they were still in Canaan, and when they came to a place
        called Geliloth[[COMMENT(0)]] near the Jordan River, the men of Reuben, Gad,
        and the half-tribe of Manasseh stopped to build a large and imposing altar.  '
      comments:
      - number: '22:10 '
        content: Or <b>to the circle of stones; </b>similarly in 22:11.
    - title: 
      content: 'The rest of Israel heard that the people of Reuben, Gad, and the
        half-tribe of Manasseh had built an altar at Geliloth at the edge of the
        land of Canaan, on the west side of the Jordan River. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the whole community of Israel gathered at Shiloh and prepared
        to go to war against them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'First, however, they sent a delegation led by Phinehas son of Eleazar,
        the priest, to talk with the tribes of Reuben, Gad, and the half-tribe of
        Manasseh. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'In this delegation were ten leaders of Israel, one from each of the
        ten tribes, and each the head of his family within the clans of Israel.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When they arrived in the land of Gilead, they said to the tribes
        of Reuben, Gad, and the half-tribe of Manasseh, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThe whole community of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> demands
        to know why you are betraying the God of Israel. How could you turn away
        from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and build an altar for yourselves in
        rebellion against him? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Was our sin at Peor not enough? To this day we are not fully cleansed
        of it, even after the plague that struck the entire community of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And yet today you are turning away from following the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.
        If you rebel against the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> today, he will be angry
        with all of us tomorrow.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIf you need the altar because the land you possess is defiled,
        then join us in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s land, where the Tabernacle
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> is situated, and share our land with us.
        But do not rebel against the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> or against us by
        building an altar other than the one true altar of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        our God. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Didn\u2019t divine anger fall on the entire community of Israel when
        Achan, a member of the clan of Zerah, sinned by stealing the things set apart
        for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>? He was not
        the only one who died because of his sin.\u201D</smallcaps>  "
      comments:
      - number: '22:20 '
        content: The Hebrew term used here refers to the complete consecration of
          things or people to the <span class="ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf">Lord</span>,
          either by destroying them or by giving them as an offering.
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the people of Reuben, Gad, and the half-tribe of Manasseh answered
        the heads of the clans of Israel: '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the Mighty One, is God! The
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the Mighty One, is God! He knows the truth,
        and may Israel know it, too! We have not built the altar in treacherous rebellion
        against the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. If we have done so, do not spare
        our lives this day. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'If we have built an altar for ourselves to turn away from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        or to offer burnt offerings or grain offerings or peace offerings, may the
        <smallcaps>Lord </smallcaps>himself punish us.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThe truth is, we have built this altar because we fear that
        in the future your descendants will say to ours, \u2018What right do you
        have to worship the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of Israel? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has placed the Jordan River as a
        barrier between our people and you people of Reuben and Gad. You have no
        claim to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.\u2019 So your descendants may prevent
        our descendants from worshiping the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSo we decided to build the altar, not for burnt offerings or
        sacrifices, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "but as a memorial. It will remind our descendants and your descendants
        that we, too, have the right to worship the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> at
        his sanctuary with our burnt offerings, sacrifices, and peace offerings.
        Then your descendants will not be able to say to ours, \u2018You have no
        claim to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIf they say this, our descendants can reply, \u2018Look at
        this copy of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s altar that our ancestors
        made. It is not for burnt offerings or sacrifices; it is a reminder of the
        relationship both of us have with the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Far be it from us to rebel against the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        or turn away from him by building our own altar for burnt offerings, grain
        offerings, or sacrifices. Only the altar of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        our God that stands in front of the Tabernacle may be used for that purpose.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When Phinehas the priest and the leaders of the community\u2014the
        heads of the clans of Israel\u2014heard this from the tribes of Reuben, Gad,
        and the half-tribe of Manasseh, they were satisfied. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Phinehas son of Eleazar, the priest, replied to them, \u201CToday
        we know the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> is among us because you have not
        committed this treachery against the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> as we thought.
        Instead, you have rescued Israel from being destroyed by the hand of the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Phinehas son of Eleazar, the priest, and the other leaders left
        the tribes of Reuben and Gad in Gilead and returned to the land of Canaan
        to tell the Israelites what had happened. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And all the Israelites were satisfied and praised God and spoke no
        more of war against Reuben and Gad.  '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "Joshua\u2019s Final Words to Israel"
      content: '  The years passed, and the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had given
        the people of Israel rest from all their enemies. Joshua, who was now very
        old, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "called together all the elders, leaders, judges, and officers of
        Israel. He said to them, \u201CI am now a very old man. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You have seen everything the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God
        has done for you during my lifetime. The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your
        God has fought for you against your enemies. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I have allotted to you as your homeland all the land of the nations
        yet unconquered, as well as the land of those we have already conquered\u2014from
        the Jordan River to the Mediterranean Sea[[COMMENT(0)]] in the west. "
      comments:
      - number: '23:4 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Great Sea.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'This land will be yours, for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your
        God will himself drive out all the people living there now. You will take
        possession of their land, just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God
        promised you.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSo be very careful to follow everything Moses wrote in the
        Book of Instruction. Do not deviate from it, turning either to the right
        or to the left. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Make sure you do not associate with the other people still remaining
        in the land. Do not even mention the names of their gods, much less swear
        by them or serve them or worship them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Rather, cling tightly to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God
        as you have done until now.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CFor the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has driven out great and
        powerful nations for you, and no one has yet been able to defeat you. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Each one of you will put to flight a thousand of the enemy, for the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God fights for you, just as he has promised. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So be very careful to love the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut if you turn away from him and cling to the customs of the
        survivors of these nations remaining among you, and if you intermarry with
        them, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'then know for certain that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God
        will no longer drive them out of your land. Instead, they will be a snare
        and a trap to you, a whip for your backs and thorny brambles in your eyes,
        and you will vanish from this good land the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your
        God has given you.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSoon I will die, going the way of everything on earth. Deep
        in your hearts you know that every promise of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        your God has come true. Not a single one has failed! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But as surely as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God has given
        you the good things he promised, he will also bring disaster on you if you
        disobey him. He will completely destroy you from this good land he has given
        you. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Covenant Renewed"
      content: '  Then Joshua summoned all the tribes of Israel to Shechem, including
        their elders, leaders, judges, and officers. So they came and presented themselves
        to God.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Joshua said to the people, \u201CThis is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of Israel, says: Long ago your ancestors, including Terah, the father
        of Abraham and Nahor, lived beyond the Euphrates River,[[COMMENT(0)]] and
        they worshiped other gods. "
      comments:
      - number: '24:2 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the river; </b>also in 24:3, 14, 15.
    - title: 
      content: 'But I took your ancestor Abraham from the land beyond the Euphrates
        and led him into the land of Canaan. I gave him many descendants through
        his son Isaac. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'To Isaac I gave Jacob and Esau. To Esau I gave the mountains of Seir,
        while Jacob and his children went down into Egypt.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThen I sent Moses and Aaron, and I brought terrible plagues
        on Egypt; and afterward I brought you out as a free people. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But when your ancestors arrived at the Red Sea,[[COMMENT(0)]] the
        Egyptians chased after you with chariots and charioteers. '
      comments:
      - number: '24:6 '
        content: Hebrew <b>sea of reeds.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'When your ancestors cried out to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        I put darkness between you and the Egyptians. I brought the sea crashing
        down on the Egyptians, drowning them. With your very own eyes you saw what
        I did. Then you lived in the wilderness for many years.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CFinally, I brought you into the land of the Amorites on the
        east side of the Jordan. They fought against you, but I destroyed them before
        you. I gave you victory over them, and you took possession of their land. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Balak son of Zippor, king of Moab, started a war against Israel.
        He summoned Balaam son of Beor to curse you, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'but I would not listen to him. Instead, I made Balaam bless you,
        and so I rescued you from Balak.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhen you crossed the Jordan River and came to Jericho, the
        men of Jericho fought against you, as did the Amorites, the Perizzites, the
        Canaanites, the Hittites, the Girgashites, the Hivites, and the Jebusites.
        But I gave you victory over them. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And I sent terror[[COMMENT(0)]] ahead of you to drive out the two
        kings of the Amorites. It was not your swords or bows that brought you victory. '
      comments:
      - number: '24:12 '
        content: Often rendered <b>the hornet. </b>The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - title: 
      content: "I gave you land you had not worked on, and I gave you towns you did
        not build\u2014the towns where you are now living. I gave you vineyards and
        olive groves for food, though you did not plant them.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSo fear the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and serve him wholeheartedly.
        Put away forever the idols your ancestors worshiped when they lived beyond
        the Euphrates River and in Egypt. Serve the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> alone. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But if you refuse to serve the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, then
        choose today whom you will serve. Would you prefer the gods your ancestors
        served beyond the Euphrates? Or will it be the gods of the Amorites in whose
        land you now live? But as for me and my family, we will serve the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The people replied, \u201CWe would never abandon the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        and serve other gods. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> our God is the one who rescued
        us and our ancestors from slavery in the land of Egypt. He performed mighty
        miracles before our very eyes. As we traveled through the wilderness among
        our enemies, he preserved us. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "It was the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> who drove out the Amorites
        and the other nations living here in the land. So we, too, will serve the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, for he alone is our God.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Joshua warned the people, \u201CYou are not able to serve the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, for he is a holy and jealous God. He will not
        forgive your rebellion and your sins. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "If you abandon the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and serve other gods,
        he will turn against you and destroy you, even though he has been so good
        to you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the people answered Joshua, \u201CNo, we will serve the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou are a witness to your own decision,\u201D Joshua said.
        \u201CYou have chosen to serve the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.\u201D\u201CYes,\u201D
        they replied, \u201Cwe are witnesses to what we have said.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAll right then,\u201D Joshua said, \u201Cdestroy the idols
        among you, and turn your hearts to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God
        of Israel.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The people said to Joshua, \u201CWe will serve the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        our God. We will obey him alone.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Joshua made a covenant with the people that day at Shechem, committing
        them to follow the decrees and regulations of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Joshua recorded these things in the Book of God\u2019s Instructions.
        As a reminder of their agreement, he took a huge stone and rolled it beneath
        the terebinth tree beside the Tabernacle of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Joshua said to all the people, \u201CThis stone has heard everything
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to us. It will be a witness to testify
        against you if you go back on your word to God.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: Leaders Buried in the Promised Land
      content: 'Then Joshua sent all the people away to their own homelands.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After this, Joshua son of Nun, the servant of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        died at the age of 110. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They buried him in the land he had been allocated, at Timnath-serah
        in the hill country of Ephraim, north of Mount Gaash.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The people of Israel served the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> throughout
        the lifetime of Joshua and of the elders who outlived him\u2014those who
        had personally experienced all that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had done
        for Israel.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The bones of Joseph, which the Israelites had brought along with
        them when they left Egypt, were buried at Shechem, in the plot of land Jacob
        had bought from the sons of Hamor for 100 pieces of silver.[[COMMENT(0)]]
        This land was located in the territory allotted to the descendants of Joseph.  '
      comments:
      - number: '24:32 '
        content: Hebrew <b>100 kesitahs; </b>the value or weight of the kesitah is
          no longer known.
